---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { internalHref, siteMeta } from "@/lib/site";
---

<BaseLayout title="SDK Layout" description="What the Kern SDK archive contains, how release artifacts are split, and why the packaged toolchain layout is explicit.">
  <section class="manual-page mx-auto px-5 pb-20 pt-14 md:px-8 md:pt-18">
    <div class="eyebrow">SDK Layout</div>
    <h1 class="mt-6 max-w-4xl text-5xl leading-[0.95] text-[color:var(--kern-ink)] md:text-6xl">
      SDK layout and artifacts
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[color:var(--kern-text-muted)]">
      This page describes what the released SDK contains, how it is laid out on disk,
      and how that differs from standalone toolchain artifacts and editor packaging.
    </p>

    <div class="manual-callout mt-10">
      <div class="manual-kicker">SDK Summary</div>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-base">
        <li>The SDK archive is the normal user-facing release artifact.</li>
        <li>The standalone toolchain archive exists for CI, bootstrap, and controlled validation.</li>
        <li>The VSIX is an editor integration artifact, not a replacement for the SDK itself.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Three release artifacts, three different jobs</h2>
      <div class="manual-grid manual-grid-3 mt-6">
        <section>
          <div class="manual-kicker">SDK archive</div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-base">
            This is the normal artifact users install. It contains the Kern tools, the shipped library layers, and the packaged host toolchain layout.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <div class="manual-kicker">Standalone toolchain archive</div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-base">
            This is mainly for CI, bootstrap, and controlled host-tool validation. It is not the normal first thing an end user should download.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <div class="manual-kicker">VSIX / editor artifact</div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-base">
            The editor extension is a separate artifact that can bundle a platform-specific `kern-lsp`, but it does not replace the SDK.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Current SDK directory shape</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base">
        The active release layout is deliberately moving toward a real SDK shape instead of ad-hoc packaging scripts.
        The current archive already exposes the important structure directly.
      </p>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`kern-<version>-<host-target>/
  bin/
  lib/kern/
  manifest/sdk.json
  toolchain/
    host/
      bin/
      lib/
      include/
      sysroot/`}</code></pre>
      <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-base">
        <li>`bin/` contains the host-facing Kern tools: `kernc`, `craft`, and `kern-lsp`.</li>
        <li>`lib/kern/` contains the official shipped library layers: `base`, `sys`, `rt`, and `std`.</li>
        <li>`manifest/sdk.json` records the SDK layout and the toolchain resolution metadata.</li>
        <li>`toolchain/host/` contains the packaged host LLVM/Clang prefix used for release validation.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <div class="manual-grid manual-grid-2">
        <section>
          <h2 class="text-3xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">What `sdk.json` is for</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 text-base">
            `manifest/sdk.json` is the structured description of the installed SDK:
            binaries, library layers, toolchain layout, resolution strategy, and bundled component paths.
          </p>
          <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-base">
            <li>It records the SDK version and host target.</li>
            <li>It records the toolchain resolver order.</li>
            <li>It records whether the SDK is bundled-first or system-fallback.</li>
            <li>It records the current packaged layout paths under `toolchain/host/`.</li>
            <li>It can also carry per-component checksum and size metadata for packaged toolchain entries.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
          <div class="manual-kicker">Why the packaged toolchain exists</div>
          <p class="mt-4 text-base">
            The release model is trying to remove dependence on lucky host state. That is why the SDK prefers the packaged host toolchain when present.
          </p>
          <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-base">
            <li>It keeps the release environment closer to the environment users actually execute.</li>
            <li>It stops release quality from depending on whatever LLVM happens to be on a CI runner.</li>
            <li>It gives source-build and ambient PATH usage a lower-priority fallback role instead of making them the primary install path.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Toolchain resolution order</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base">
        The intended installed-SDK behavior is already explicit. When `kernc` needs a host toolchain, the current resolver order is:
      </p>
      <ol class="mt-5 list-decimal space-y-3 pl-5 text-base">
        <li>explicit `--toolchain-root`</li>
        <li>SDK-relative bundled toolchain</li>
        <li>explicit environment overrides</li>
        <li>system `PATH`</li>
      </ol>
      <p class="mt-5 text-base">
        That order matters because it makes the installed SDK self-describing and relocatable, while still leaving source-build and local override escape hatches available.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <div class="manual-grid manual-grid-2">
        <section>
          <h2 class="text-3xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">What is bundled, and what is not</h2>
          <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-base">
            <li>The packaged host LLVM/Clang prefix lives under `toolchain/host/`.</li>
            <li>The Kern tools and official library layers live in the SDK root itself.</li>
            <li>Platform SDKs and libc baselines are still host responsibilities unless Kern explicitly vendors them later.</li>
            <li>That is why a bundled toolchain does not remove every host runtime dependency question.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
          <div class="manual-kicker">Why some archives are large</div>
          <p class="mt-4 text-base">
            The SDK is intentionally heavier than a bare three-binary download because it carries the packaged host toolchain layout.
            On Windows in particular, first install can take noticeable time because the archive is large and antivirus scanning can be aggressive.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <div class="manual-grid manual-grid-2">
        <section>
          <div class="manual-kicker">This also explains the install scripts</div>
          <p class="mt-4 text-base">
            The user-facing contract stays native: `install.sh` on Unix and `install.ps1` on Windows.
            The Python `ops` entrypoints remain the canonical repository and CI control flow, but they are not the user-facing install contract.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <div class="manual-kicker">What this page is trying to make explicit</div>
          <p class="mt-4 text-base">
            The release model is intentionally concrete: a visible SDK layout, visible manifest, visible host-tool payload,
            and a clean distinction between user install artifacts, repository packaging flow, and editor integration.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Related documents</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base">
        This page covers the public SDK shape. More detailed release engineering policy still lives in the repository docs for now.
      </p>
      <div class="manual-links mt-6">
        <a class="button-primary" href={internalHref("/install")}>
          Install
        </a>
        <a class="button-secondary" href={internalHref("/build-from-source")}>
          Build from source
        </a>
        <a class="button-secondary" href={`${siteMeta.repoUrl}/blob/main/docs/sdk-rebuild-plan.md`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
          SDK rebuild plan
        </a>
        <a class="button-secondary" href={`${siteMeta.repoUrl}/blob/main/docs/windows-distribution.md`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
          Windows distribution
        </a>
        <a class="button-secondary" href={`${siteMeta.repoUrl}/blob/main/docs/unix-distribution.md`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
          Unix distribution
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
